node.contents: @heivik A good guarantee that the hashCode() provided by Object is useful can be found in the jls http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-4.html#jls-4.3.2 ____________ Also an Object has depending on the implementation several bytes overhead so the jvm could store the address the object had on creation as hashcode or it could just return 1, implementation defined. If you read that last sentence you will notice that the computation of hashcode is implementation defined only the guarantees of the spec and the javadoc have to be met, so no guarantee about how often it is computed.

node.contents: First off, the default hashcode of an object does not change after it is constructed so IdentityHashMap is not useless. Java may move objects around in memory but it doesn't change their identity hash code.

astNode.text: First off, the default hashcode of an object does not change after it is constructed so IdentityHashMap is not useless. Java may move objects around in memory but it doesn't change their identity hash code.

node.contents: Secondly, if you don't define your own equals() method, then every object you construct will be not equals() to every other. This means if you want to use them as keys in a HashMap (or IdentityHashMap) you'll only be able to retrieve them by using the original object.

astNode.text: Secondly, if you don't define your own equals() method, then every object you construct will be not equals() to every other. This means if you want to use them as keys in a HashMap (or IdentityHashMap) you'll only be able to retrieve them by using the original object.
